This proposal is within the field of human-computer interaction and physical rehabilitation.

Improvements in healthcare mean that people live longer and survive many injuries. Still, increasing numbers of people need to undertake physiotherapy at some point in their lifetime, many during long periods of time. While highly beneficial, it is costly. Improving the quality and efficiency of rehabilitation programs is one of the fundamental strategies for a better and cost-effective healthcare system. 

Interactive and digital technologies promise to make rehabilitation procedures more engaging and effective. While many systems have been proposed in the last decade, few are in use in today’s rehabilitation centers. In fact, there has been little discussion of associated sociotechnical issues that are crucial for technology success in this context. To fill this knowledge gap, your goal is to understand the determinants of physiotherapy technology adoption from these aspects by applying technology acceptance theories.

You will continue previous work that developed prototypes aimed at 1) assisting patients with rehabilitation exercises and 2) assisting physiotherapists in monitoring multiple patients. Your work will focus on creating a “workstation” that can be deployed in the field. You will then conduct field research through ethnographical observations, interviews, and surveys.

Tasks that you will undertake include:
- Task 1 – Literature review;
- Task 2 – Get acquainted with interactive technologies and prototyping tools;
- Task 3 – Improve current prototypes;
- Task 4 – Deploy prototype in a rehabilitation center (Centro de Investigação Interdisciplinar Egas Moniz);
- Task 5 – Understand the adoption process of both patients and professionals;
- Task 6 – Write master thesis.

In addition to your master thesis, you are expected to advance state of the art in the field of human-computer interaction and submit a paper to an international conference or journal.

